"But, nobis non licet esse tam disertis, at least if wg study to refine our numbers. I have long had by me the mateiials of an English ¢ Prosodia,’ con- taining all the mechanical rales of versification, wherein [ have treated, with some exactness, of the feet, the quantities, and the pauses. The French and Italians know nothing of the two first; at least their best poets have not practised them. As for the pauses, Matherbe first brought them into France within this last century : and we see how thiey adorn their Alexandrines. But, as Virgil propounds a riddle, whicli he leaves unsolved—"